\f0\fs24 \cf0 The systematics of \cf2 lobose testate amoebae (Arcellinida)\cf0 , a diverse group of shelled free-living \cf2 unicellular eukaryotes\cf0 , is still mostly based on morphological criteria such as shell shape and composition. Few molecular \cf3 phylogenetic studies\cf0 have been performed on these organisms to date, and their \cf3 phylogeny\cf0 suffers from typical under-sampling artefacts, \b resulting \b0 in a still mostly unresolved \cf4 tree\cf0 . In order to \b clarify \b0 the \cf3 phylogenetic relationships\cf0 \b among \b0 \cf2 arcellinid testate amoebae \cf0 at the inter-generic and inter-specific level, and to evaluate the validity of the criteria used for taxonomy, we \b amplified \b0 and \b sequenced \b0 the \cf4 SSU rRNA gene\cf0 of nine taxa - \cf2 Difflugia bacillariarum\cf0 , \cf2 D. hiraethogii, D. acuminata, D. lanceolata, D. achlora, Bullinularia gracilis, Netzelia oviformis, Physochila griseol\cf0 a and \cf2 Cryptodifflugia oviformis\cf0 . Our results, combined with existing data demonstrate the following: 1) Most \cf2 arcellinids\cf0 are divided into two major clades, 2) the genus \cf2 Difflugia\cf0 is not monophyletic, and the genera \cf2 Netzelia\cf0 and \cf2 Arcella\cf0 are closely related, and 3) Cryptodifflugia branches at the base of the Arcellinida clade. These results contradict the traditional taxonomy based on shell composition, and emphasize the importance of general shell shape in the taxonomy of \cf2 arcellinid testate amoebae\cf0 .\ }
